SIMPLE: similitude
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Similitude
<hw>Si*mil"i*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>similitude</ets>, L. <ets>similitudo</ets>, from <ets>similis</ets>
similar. See <er>Similar</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or
state of being similar or like; resemblance; likeness; similarity;
<as>as, <ex>similitude</ex> of substance</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us make now man in our image, man⟦br⟧
In our <qex>similitude</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If fate some future bard shall join⟦br⟧
In sad <qex>similitude</qex> of griefs to mine.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of likening, or that which likens, one thing
to another; fanciful or imaginative comparison; a simile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tasso, in his <qex>similitudes</qex>, never departed from the
woods; that is, all his comparisons were taken from the country.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is like or similar; a representation,
semblance, or copy; a facsimile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man should wed his <qex>similitude</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Similitudinary</ent>⟦br⟧
